#compdef glci
# =============================================================================
# glci — Maxime Dubourg's "Ease GitLab CI Pipelines
#          set-up by running your jobs locally in
#          Docker containers" — a Node.js CLI that
#          parses a `.gitlab-ci.yml` file, resolves
#          its job/stage/include/cache/artifacts
#          semantics against the GitLab CI reference,
#          and EXECUTES the resulting pipeline locally
#          by spawning Docker containers (one per job,
#          tagged with the job's `image:` directive)
#          via the Docker Engine API.  Lets developers
#          test pipeline changes WITHOUT push-and-wait-
#          for-GitLab-runner round-trips that otherwise
#          dominate CI-iteration time.
#          Distinguishing from `gitlab-runner exec`
#          (gitlab-runner's bundled exec subcommand;
#          requires installing the full gitlab-runner
#          binary; mimics shared-runner environment),
#          gitlab-ci-local (firecow/gitlab-ci-local;
#          newer + more actively maintained TS-Node
#          competitor; richer feature set), Earthly
#          (Earthfile-based CI alternative; different
#          DSL not GitLab YAML), Act (nektos/act for
#          GitHub Actions; GitHub-specific, not
#          GitLab), and the canonical "push-to-feature-
#          branch-and-wait-for-CI" iteration loop by:
#            - DOCKERODE FOUNDATION — uses apocas/
#              dockerode ^3.2 (this is the headline
#              CLI library that CLOSES Axis 44 on
#              the TS-Node side at 1/1/1; see
#              taxonomy notes below) for ALL Docker
#              Engine API operations: image pull
#              (`docker.pull(image)`), container
#              create (`docker.createContainer(opts)`),
#              container.exec for command execution
#              inside the job's container, stream
#              demuxing of stdout/stderr, container
#              wait/inspect for exit code
#            - GITLAB-CI-YML PARSER — uses js-yaml
#              v4 to parse `.gitlab-ci.yml`; supports
#              `stages:` declaration, `image:` global
#              + per-job, `before_script:` /
#              `after_script:` / `script:`, `cache:`,
#              `artifacts:`, `services:`, `variables:`,
#              `include:`, `extends:`, `only:` /
#              `except:` (basic), `when:`, GitLab's
#              `RESERVED_JOB_NAMES` filtering, and
#              the `default:` global block per the
#              GitLab CI YAML reference
#            - PRE-DEFINED VARIABLES — `src/pre-
#              defined.js` populates GitLab's
#              `CI_PROJECT_PATH`, `CI_COMMIT_REF_NAME`,
#              `CI_COMMIT_SHA`, `CI_PIPELINE_ID`,
#              `CI_RUNNER_TAGS`, etc. by querying
#              `git` via nodegit and parsing the
#              current repo's branch + commit
#              metadata.  Jobs see the same env-vars
#              they would on a real GitLab runner
#            - .ENV INTEGRATION — automatically reads
#              `.env` files in the working directory
#              via dotenv v8; the parsed variables
#              are injected into job containers
#              alongside the GitLab pre-defined ones
#              (useful for development secrets that
#              would be GitLab CI/CD variables in
#              production)
#            - PIPELINE GRAPH RENDERING — uses
#              chalk + the bundled `drawPipeline()`
#              helper to render the resolved
#              pipeline as a colored ASCII graph
#              before execution begins; shows
#              stages + jobs + dependencies; lets
#              users sanity-check the pipeline
#              structure visually
#            - JOB FILTERING via --only-jobs — `--
#              only-jobs build:assets,test:lint`
#              runs only the listed jobs (skipping
#              the rest of the pipeline); useful
#              for iterating on a single job
#              without rebuilding the full graph
#            - CUSTOM .yml PATH via --yml — `--yml
#              ci/test-pipeline.yml` runs against
#              a non-default pipeline file (useful
#              for monorepos with multiple
#              pipelines)
#            - CUSTOM WORK DIR via --dir — `--dir
#              ./my-glci-workspace` overrides the
#              default `.glci/` directory for
#              cache + artifacts + intermediate
#              state; useful for keeping multiple
#              concurrent glci runs separate
#            - ARTIFACT PROPAGATION — glci honors
#              GitLab's `artifacts:` directive +
#              propagates artifacts between
#              stages by mounting an
#              `.glci_artifacts/` shared volume
#              into successor job containers
#            - CACHE PROPAGATION — `.glci_cache/`
#              is mounted into each job per the
#              job's `cache:` paths; subsequent
#              runs reuse the cache without re-
#              downloading dependencies
#            - SHELL COMMAND DEMUXING — the
#              bundled `execCommands` helper uses
#              dockerode's `modem.demuxStream()` to
#              separate stdout (printed normal) from
#              stderr (printed in red via chalk)
#              when streaming `docker exec` output
#            - SHEBANG PRESERVATION via rollup-plugin-
#              preserve-shebang — the bundled CLI
#              keeps its `#!/usr/bin/env node`
#              shebang through the rollup
#              minification step (rolled CLIs lose
#              their shebang by default)
#            - 580+ STARS ON mdubourg001/glci — solid
#              community traction for a single-
#              maintainer Node CLI; active
#              maintenance through 2026 by Maxime
#              Dubourg (Bordeaux, France)
#          Used by: GitLab CI users tired of the
#          push-and-wait iteration loop, developers
#          maintaining `.gitlab-ci.yml` files who
#          want fast feedback on syntax + behavior
#          changes, CI/CD authors prototyping new
#          pipelines before committing them to
#          production, and teams running self-hosted
#          GitLab who don't want to spawn ephemeral
#          runners for every iteration test.
#
# Author:  Maxime Dubourg (mdubourg001 on GitHub;
#          https://maximedubourg.com); based in
#          Bordeaux, France.
# Source:  https://github.com/mdubourg001/glci
#          https://github.com/mdubourg001/glci/blob/main/index.js
#          https://github.com/mdubourg001/glci/blob/main/src/constants.js
#          https://github.com/mdubourg001/glci/blob/main/package.json
# Manpage: No traditional manpage; `glci --help`
#          shows yargs-generated help for the CLI
#          flags.  Full design notes in repo README.md.
# Library: dockerode ^3.2.1 (apocas/dockerode —
#          Pedro Dias's "Docker.io Node.js modular
#          API").  This is the headline dependency
#          for this completion's axis-44 closing
#          role; see taxonomy notes below.  Also
#          yargs ^16 (Axis 1 argparse), js-yaml ^4
#          (Axis 11 YAML parsing), nodegit ^0.27
#          (Axis 43 alternative pure-Rust binding
#          to libgit2 for Node — used for git
#          metadata gathering), chalk ^4 (terminal
#          coloring), deepmerge ^4.2 (config
#          merging), dotenv ^8 (.env file parsing),
#          fs-extra ^9 (filesystem helpers), glob
#          ^7 (file globbing for cache/artifacts
#          paths), slugify ^1.5 (job-name to
#          container-name slugging), uvu ^0.5
#          (testing framework).
# License: MIT
# Status:  580+ stars on mdubourg001/glci; active
#          development (latest commit 2026-05-20);
#          version 0.5.1; published to npm as
#          `glci`.
#
