#     leader-bump rounds.  Compare to the 90-library
#     landmark crossed at R729-R731 by all three
#     languages
#
# WHY dockerode IS A DISTINCTIVE AXIS-44 CLOSER:
#
#   apocas/dockerode by Pedro Dias is the *original*
#   Node.js Docker Engine API client (started 2014)
#   and remains the dominant choice for Node Docker
#   tools.  Distinguishing characteristics in the
#   TS-Node ecosystem:
#     1. MODULAR API — each Docker resource
#        (containers, images, networks, volumes,
#        plugins, secrets, configs, services,
#        tasks, swarm, nodes) is exposed as its own
#        prototype with operation methods.  Users
#        can `require('dockerode')` and get the
#        full API surface
#     2. PROMISE + CALLBACK + STREAM TRIPLE API —
#        every operation supports BOTH a Node-style
#        callback (`docker.listContainers(cb)`) AND
#        a Promise return (`await docker.
#        listContainers()`) AND streaming for
#        long-running operations (logs, exec
#        attach).  Users pick the style that fits
#        their existing code
#     3. MODEM ABSTRACTION — the underlying HTTP/
#        Unix-socket transport is abstracted behind
#        a `Modem` object that handles protocol
#        upgrades (for hijacked-protocol exec
#        sessions), stream demuxing, content-type
#        negotiation, etc.  Users rarely interact
#        with Modem directly but it's there for
#        edge cases
#     4. STREAM DEMUXING — the dockerode-bundled
#        `modem.demuxStream(stream, stdout, stderr)`
#        helper separates Docker's multiplexed
#        stdout/stderr stream into separate
#        destinations.  No other Docker client
#        library makes this as ergonomic
#     5. CROSS-RUNTIME — works in Node.js, Deno
#        (via npm: prefix), and Bun.  All-JS
#        portability
#     6. ~4,500+ STARS ON apocas/dockerode
#     7. UNIVERSAL PRODUCTION USAGE — used by glci
#        (this completion), balena-cli (IoT
#        platform CLI), httptoolkit-server, stencila
#        dockta (research reproducibility), umbrel
#        (self-hosted home server), drizzle-orm,
#        fauna-shell, nodebook, every major Node-
#        Docker integration tool
#
# Maintained by Pedro Dias (@apocas) +
# contributors at apocas/dockerode.  License:
# Apache-2.0.
#
# Comparison to other Axis 44 candidates (TS-Node):
#   * glci (R767 THIS) — Maxime Dubourg's GitLab CI
#     local runner with dockerode as direct dep;
#     580 stars; clear Docker-centric use case
#   * dockly (lirantal) — already in corpus as
#     _dockly
#   * balena-cli — IoT platform CLI; 512 stars but
#     much broader scope than just Docker
#   * dockta (stencila) — Docker image builder for
#     researchers; 124 stars; niche use case
#   * httptoolkit-server — backend of HTTP Toolkit;
#     550 stars but Docker is incidental
#   * nodebook (netgusto) — multi-lang REPL; 1,646
#     stars but more of an editor than a Docker tool
#   * sematext-agent-docker — metrics collector;
#     208 stars; agent not CLI
#   * dockerode itself ships no CLI
#
# glci is the chosen Axis 44 TS-Node closer
# because:
#   - It declares dockerode as a DIRECT runtime
#     dependency in package.json (`dockerode
#     ^3.2.1`)
#   - The GitLab CI local-execution use case
#     exercises the FULL dockerode pipeline:
#     image pull, container create with env-vars,
#     exec command with stream demuxing,
#     container inspect for exit code, container
#     remove for cleanup
#   - The pure-JS implementation (no native
#     bindings beyond dockerode's HTTP socket
#     wrapper) demonstrates the cross-platform
#     advantage of the Node Docker ecosystem
#   - 580 stars + active maintenance + clean
#     single-purpose CLI architecture make it a
#     stable taxonomy choice
#   - It is the closest functional analog to
#     dockrtui (R765) and dobi (R766) on the
#     "Docker-API-as-headline-library" pattern,
#     specifically representing the CI-SIMULATION
#     use case (vs dashboard / vs build
#     orchestration)
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# THE glci CLI
#
# glci is a single-command CLI built on yargs.
# Invocation:
#   glci [--yml <path>] [--dir <path>] [--only-jobs <list>]
#
# Operating model:
# - Looks for `.gitlab-ci.yml` in cwd (override with
#   `--yml`)
# - Looks for `.env` in cwd (auto-loaded if present)
# - Creates `.glci/` workspace (override with `--dir`)
#   containing `.glci_cache/` + `.glci_artifacts/`
#   between-stage propagation
# - Spawns one Docker container per job using the
#   job's declared `image:`
# - Runs `before_script + script + after_script` in
#   the container via docker exec
# - Mounts cache + artifacts into successor jobs
# - Reports per-job stdout (normal) + stderr (red)
#
# Flags:
#   --yml <PATH>                      path to GitLab
#                                     CI YAML file
#                                     (default
#                                     .gitlab-ci.yml)
#   --dir <PATH>                      base directory
#                                     for glci
#                                     workspace
#                                     (default .glci)
#   --only-jobs <JOB1,JOB2,...>       run only the
#                                     listed jobs
#                                     (comma-
#                                     separated)
#   --help                            yargs help
#   --version                         yargs version
#
# Environment:
#   .env                              auto-loaded
#                                     (cwd)
#   Docker socket                     default /var/
#                                     run/docker.sock
#                                     unless
#                                     DOCKER_HOST is
#                                     set
#
# GitLab CI/CD predefined variables auto-populated:
#   CI_PROJECT_PATH
#   CI_COMMIT_REF_NAME
#   CI_COMMIT_SHA
#   CI_PIPELINE_ID
#   CI_RUNNER_TAGS
#   ... (the full GitLab predefined set)
#
# Common invocations:
#   # Run the full pipeline against .gitlab-ci.yml in cwd
#   glci
#
#   # Use a non-default pipeline file
#   glci --yml ci/integration.yml
#
#   # Use a custom workspace directory
#   glci --dir /tmp/glci-workspace
#
#   # Run only specific jobs (skip the rest)
#   glci --only-jobs build:assets,test:lint
#
#   # Combine flags
#   glci --yml ci/release.yml --dir .glci-release \
#       --only-jobs build,test
#
#   # Show help
#   glci --help
#
# OPTIONS (sourced directly from
# https://github.com/mdubourg001/glci/blob/main/src/constants.js):
#
#   --yml <PATH>                      .gitlab-ci.yml path
#   --dir <PATH>                      .glci/ workspace path
#   --only-jobs <JOB1,JOB2>           job allowlist
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

local curcontext="$curcontext" state line ret=1
typeset -A opt_args

_arguments -C \
    '(- *)--help[show help]' \
    '(- *)--version[show version]' \
    '--yml=[path to GitLab CI YAML file (default .gitlab-ci.yml)]:yml file:_files -g "*.(yml|yaml)"' \
    '--dir=[base directory for glci workspace (default .glci)]:dir:_directories' \
    '--only-jobs=[run only the listed jobs (comma-separated)]:jobs: ' \
    && ret=0

return ret
